@NODE "INSTALLATION" "Dialup - Installation"
@NEXT "WINDOWS"
@PREF "REGISTRATION"
@TOC  "MAIN"

A few words concerning the installation
***************************************

Copy  the  files Dialup and Dialup.key (if you own it) to any directory. If
you do not have installed the gtlayout.library by Olaf 'Olsen' Barthel yet,
copy it to your Libs:-directory.

But the most easy way is to use the Commodore Installer in the package.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "WINDOWS" "Dialup - Windows"
@NEXT "WIN-MAIN"
@PREF "INSTALLATION"
@TOC  "MAIN"

Windows
*******

All  windows  and  buttons  are  taxable  by  keyboard.  Buttons, which are
highlighted with an additional border can be activated with Return.

All explanations and configerations refer to the english texts and keys.

@{" Main     " LINK "WIN-MAIN"    }                                                 The main window
@{" Settings " LINK "WIN-SETTINGS"}                     The settings window for the different hosts
@{" Dial     " LINK "WIN-DIAL"    }                                                 The dial window
@ENDNODE

@NODE "WIN-MAIN" "Dialup - Windows/Main"
@NEXT "WIN-SETTINGS"
@PREF "WINDOWS"
@TOC  "MAIN"

The main window
***************

@{b}Add@{ub}

  Adds  a  new entry with the name "--Unknown--" at the end of the list. It
  will get the default settings.


@{b}Copy@{ub}

  Copys the current entry to the end of the list.


@{b}Delete@{ub}

  Opens  a  requester,  in  which you can choose, if you want to delete the
  current or all selected entries, or if you want to cancel.


@{b}Default@{ub}

  Opens  a  requester,  in  which  you  can  choose, if you want to set the
  current  or  all  selected entries back to the default entries, or if you
  want to cancel.


@{b}Tag/Untag@{ub}

  Selects or deselects the current entry. Press the key SHIFT in additional
  and all antries will be selected or deselected.


@{b}Settings@{ub}

  Opens a window, in which you can change the settings of the current entry
  (Look at @{" Settings " LINK "WIN-SETTINGS"}).


@{b}|<@{ub}

  Sets the current entry at first place.


@{b}>|@{ub}

  Sets the current entry at the last place.


@{b}<@{ub}

  Moves the current entry up.


@{b}>@{ub}

  Moves the current entry down.


@{b}Dial@{ub}

  Opens  the  dial  window  and  tries to connect with a selected entry. If
  there is no entry selected, the current entry will be selected and dialed
  (Look at @{" Dial " LINK "WIN-DIAL"}).


@{b}Load...@{ub}

  Opens a settings box. With this, you can load an other configuaration. If
  the  current  configuration  were  changed,  but  not  saved, you will be
  reminded to save.


@{b}Save...@{ub}

  Opens a settings box. With this, you can choose the name under which your
  configuration shall be saved.

  After  you have chosen the name, you can enter, if you want the status of
  selection of the different entries saved with.


@{b}About@{ub}

  Opens the information window. If you are an registrated user, you can see
  your registration data in this window.


@{b}Quit@{ub} (or the close symbol of the window)

  Quits  the  program.  If the current configurations were changed, but not
  saved you will be reminded and enabled to cancel the action.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "WIN-SETTINGS" "Dialup - Windows/Settings"
@NEXT "SET-PROTOCOL"
@PREF "WIN-MAIN"
@TOC  "MAIN"

The settings window for the different hosts
********************************************

This  window  contains  the  individual  configuration for one host and its
hardware device.

@{" Protocol settings      " LINK "SET-PROTOCOL"}
@{" Serial settings        " LINK "SET-SERIAL"}
@{" Miscellaneous settings " LINK "SET-MISC"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SET-PROTOCOL" "Dialup - Windows/Settings/Protocol settings"
@NEXT "SET-SERIAL"
@PREF "WIN-SETTINGS"
@TOC  "MAIN"

Protocol Settings
*****************

@{b}Host@{ub}

  Name of the host for which this settings shall be valid. This name has no
  further meaning, it only serves for clearness.


@{b}IP Address@{ub}

  This parameter has only a function if the option @{b}Create@{ub} is switched on.

  The IP-Address of the own host, which is to be saved in the configuration
  of @{u}Env:Sana2/<driver>.config@{uu} if the option @{b}Create@{ub} is switched on.


@{b}Netmask@{ub}

  The netmask of the host.


@{b}Driver@{ub}

  Name  of the protocol driver, which shall be used for this host. The name
  consists of the name of the protocol and of its unit (for example: cslip0
  for  the  @{u}cslip@{uu}.device  unit @{u}0@{uu}). If the option @{b}Create@{ub} is switched on, the
  configuration with this name and an attached .config will be saved in the
  directory @{u}Env:Sana2/@{uu}.


@{b}MTU@{ub}

  This parameter has only a function if the option @{b}Create@{ub} is switched on.

  If  the  entered  amount  is  higher  than  0,  it  will  be saved in the
  configuration  of  @{u}Env:Sana2/<driver>.config@{uu}.  The  text appaers there as
  @{b}MTU=<amount>@{ub}.


@{b}CD@{ub}

  This parameter has only a function if the option @{b}Create@{ub} is switched on.

  If  this  option  is  switched  on,  the  text  @{b}CD@{ub}  will  be saved in the
  configuration of @{u}Env:Sana2/<driver>.config@{uu}.


@{b}7WIRE@{ub}

  This parameter has only a function if the option @{b}Create@{ub} is switched on.

  If  this  option  is  switched  on,  the  text @{b}7WIRE@{ub} will be saved in the
  configuration of @{u}Env:Sana2/<driver>.config@{uu}.


@{b}EOF@{ub}

  This parameter has only a function if the option @{b}Create@{ub} is switched on.

  If  this  option  is  switched  on, the text @{b}EOFMODE@{ub} will be saved in the
  configuration of @{u}Env:Sana2/<driver>.config@{uu}.


@{b}Create@{ub}

  If this option is switched on, a configuration file in @{u}Env:Sana2/@{uu} will be
  created  for the protocol after a successful dial and log in. The name of
  the file is the name of the @{b}Driver@{ub} with an additional @{u}.config@{uu}.

  In  this file the name, the unit and the baudrate of the serial device as
  well  as  the IP-Address @{b}always@{ub} will be saved. The switches CD, 7WIRE and
  EOFMODE  as  well as the MTU only will be saved, if the belonging options
  are switched on.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SET-SERIAL" "Dialup - Windows/Settings/Serial settings"
@NEXT "SET-MISC"
@PREF "SET-PROTOCOL"
@TOC  "MAIN"

Seriell Settings
****************

@{b}Hint:@{ub}

If  you  are  not going to let the configuration of the protocol be created
(look  at  @{" Protocol  settings " LINK "SET-PROTOCOL"}),please  get  sure  that  the settings for
@{b}Device@{ub}, @{b}Unit@{ub} and @{b}Baud@{ub} are in correspondence with your protocol.


@{b}Device@{ub}

  The  name  of  the  serial  device,  that shall be used for the call. The
  access is @{b}exklusiv@{ub} with the settings @{b}8N1@{ub}.


@{b}Unit@{ub}

  The Unit-number of the serial device.


@{b}Baud@{ub}

  The baudrate, with which the serial device shall run.


@{b}Init command@{ub}

  The  command,  with  which  the  Modem/Device shall be initialised. If no
  Init-command is entered, no initialisation will be done.

  At  the  Init-command  a  RETURN  is automatical attached, but not in the
  cases,  in  which  the  option  @{b}\\c@{ub}  was  entered  as  well.  For further
  information   about  the  additional  options  look  at  @{" Miscellaneous " LINK "SET-MISC"}
  @{" settings " LINK "SET-MISC"}/@{b}Parse String@{ub}.

  At  this  point  the  command AT&D0 for example, can be entered to avoid,
  that  the connection after the closing of the device does not break down.
  If your modem does not support this command, take a look at your manual.


@{b}Ignore CD@{ub}

  If  this  option  is switched on, the condition of the connection will be
  ignored.  In  the  other  case,  the  condition of the connection will be
  checked  every  3 second to see if the connection is still there and - if
  not - to interrupt the dial process.


@{b}Ignore DTR@{ub}

  If this option is switched on, an @{b}+++ATH0@{ub} will be send to the modem after
  hanging up.


@{b}7WIRE@{ub}

  If  this  option  is  switched on, the device will be opened in the @{b}7WIRE@{ub}
  (Handshake)  @{b}mode@{ub}.  Please  note  the  fact,  that  not every device does
  support this option.


@{b}Check modem init@{ub}

  If  this  option  is  switched  on,  it  will  be  checked,  if the modem
  initialisation  was  answered with an @{b}OK@{ub}. If not a new initialisaton will
  be started.

  If  you  use  the  @{b}nullmodem.device@{ub},  this  option shall be switched off,
  because the connection does take place direct.


@{b}Redial delay@{ub}

  Time in seconds, that shall be waited between dial attempts.


@{b}Timeout@{ub}

  Time  in  seconds,  that shall be waited after the dialing of a number to
  get a successful @{b}CONNECT@{ub}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SET-MISC" "Dialup - Windows/Settings/Miscellaneous settings"
@NEXT "WIN-DIAL"
@PREF "SET-SERIAL"
@TOC  "MAIN"

Miscellaneous settings
**********************

@{b}Phone number@{ub}

  At  this place you can enter the telephon number that shall be dialed. It
  is @{b}not possible@{ub} to enter @{b}several@{ub} numbers.

  The dial starts with an @{b}ATD@{ub}, the @{b}Phone number@{ub} and a @{b}RETURN@{ub}.


@{b}Parse string@{ub}

  The  parsestring will be used after a successful connection to log in the
  respective system. It must be entered as follows:

  <Wait for> <Send> <Wait for> <Send> ...

  First  the  text for which shall be waited (Capital/Small letters will be
  regarded), second the text which shall be send, if it can be found.

  Example: ogin: ghandi word: secret "" \\d\\r

  In this example, the program waits for the text "ogin:" and - if this was
  found  -  sends  the  text "ghandi". "" means, that it shall not wait for
  text.

  If  not switched of by the control sequence @{b}\\c@{ub} , after every text sent a
  @{b}RETURN@{ub} will be send as well.

  Following control sequence are possible in the send text:

    @{b}\\r@{ub} sends a <CR> (Carriage return).

    @{b}\\n@{ub} sends a <LF> (Linefeed).

    @{b}\\\\@{ub} sends a \\.

    @{b}\\t@{ub} sends a <TAB> (Tabulator).

    @{b}\\b@{ub} sends a breaksignal.

    @{b}\\d@{ub} for a little pause.

    @{b}\\s@{ub} sends a space

    @{b}\\c@{ub} switches the sending of a <CR> at the end of a text off.


@{b}Command@{ub}

  At  this point, you can enter a command, that shall be executed after the
  successful connection and the closing of the device.

  Please  note,  that @{b}Dialup@{ub} will not give the allocated memory free, until
  the executed program or script is returned.

  You  can  add  several  @{b}%-variables@{ub}  to the command, which have following
  meanings:

    @{b}%%@{ub} will be replaced by @{b}%@{ub}.

    @{b}%i@{ub} will be replaced by the @{b}IP Address@{ub}.

    @{b}%m@{ub} will be replaced by the @{b}Netmask@{ub}.

    @{b}%v@{ub} will be replaced by the @{b}Driver@{ub}.

    @{b}%M@{ub} will be replaced by the @{b}MTU@{ub}.

    @{b}%C@{ub} will be replaced by @{b}CD@{ub}, if @{b}CD@{ub} is switched on.

    @{b}%W@{ub} will be replaced by @{b}7WIRE@{ub}, if @{b}7WIRE@{ub} is switched on.

    @{b}%E@{ub} will be replaced by @{b}EOFMODE@{ub}, if @{b}EOF@{ub} is switched on.

    @{b}%d@{ub} will be replaced by the @{b}Device@{ub} name.

    @{b}%u@{ub} will be replaced by device @{b}Unit@{ub}.

    @{b}%b@{ub} will be replaced by the @{b}Baud@{ub}rate.

    @{b}%I@{ub} will be replaced by the @{b}Init command@{ub}.

    @{b}%g@{ub} will be replaced by @{b}IGNORECD@{ub}, if @{b}Ignore CD@{ub} is switched on.

    @{b}%G@{ub} will be replaced by @{b}IGNOREDTR@{ub}, if @{b}Ignore DTR@{ub} is switched on.

    @{b}%w@{ub} will be replaced by @{b}RTSCTS@{ub}, if @{b}7WIRE@{ub} is switched on.

    @{b}%y@{ub} will be replaced by the amount of @{b}Redial delay@{ub}.

    @{b}%Y@{ub} will be replaced by the amount of @{b}Timeout@{ub}.

    @{b}%p@{ub} will be replaced by @{b}Phone number@{ub}.

    @{b}%P@{ub} will be replaced by the @{b}Parse string@{uu}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "WIN-DIAL" "Dialup - Windows/Dial"
@NEXT "ARGUMENTS"
@PREF "SET-MISC"
@TOC  "MAIN"

The dial window
***************

All  selected  hosts will be dialed in a row. If a number is busy, the next
entry  will  be  dialed.  If  all  entries were dialed without success, the
dialing starts again from the beginning.

If  the connection is lost during the process of dialing or if a NO CARRIER
is found, Dialup will quit.


@{b}Connection@{ub}

  The data of the connection will be shown here, if it was realized.


@{b}Host@{ub}

  Name of the host, which is dialed to.


@{b}Number@{ub}

  Number of the host, used for dialing.


@{b}Bytes reveived@{ub}

  Amount of the received bytes.


@{b}Bytes sent@{ub}

  Amount of the bytes sent.


@{b}Expect@{ub}

  Shows the text necessary for further action of the program. Important for
  example at the parsing of the texts to log in.


@{b}Found@{ub}

  Shows the text found or the belonging error message.


@{b}Status@{ub}

  Shows the current action.


@{b}Cancel@{ub}

  Stops  the  process  of  dialing. This function probably reacts with some
  seconds delay.


@{b}Skip@{ub}

  Skips  the  current  host.  This  function  may  probably react with some
  seconds delay.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ARGUMENTS" "Dialup - Arguments"
@PREF "WIN-DIAL"
@TOC  "MAIN"

Program Arguments & Tooltypes
*****************************

The following keywords can be given to the program as @{b}ARGUMENTS@{ub} or they can
be entered as @{b}TOOLTYPES@{ub} in the program's icon.


@{b}HOST@{ub} (Tooltype: @{b}HOST@{ub})

  Name  of  the  hosts,  that  shall  be  selected.  You can use the search
  patterns  of  AmigaDOS.  Capital  and small letters will be regarded. All
  found  entries  will  be marked as selected. All in the configuration yet
  selected entries will be deselected.

  @{b}This  option  only serves to select the entries, that shall be dialed.@{ub} If
  the entry shall be dialed immediately, the option @{b}DIAL@{ub} must be given.


@{b}NOGUI/S@{ub} (Tooltype: @{b}NOGUI@{ub})

  This  switch  only  has  an effect to the dial window and to the load and
  save information. Is it given, their windows are disabled.


@{b}DIAL/S@{ub} (Tooltype: @{b}DIAL@{ub})

  Starts   the  dialing  process  immediately  after  the  loading  of  the
  configuration. Are no entries selected, the programs quits.


@{b}CFG=CONFIG/K@{ub} (Tooltype: @{b}CONFIG@{ub})

  Name of the configuration that shall be loaded.

@{b}LOG=LOGFILE/K@{ub} (Tooltype: @{b}LOGFILE@{ub})

  Name of the logfile that shall be used for the next dial.
@ENDNODE
